<% content_for :title, "jwt-pq" %>
<% content_for :description, "Post-quantum JWT signatures for Ruby. ML-DSA (FIPS 204) and hybrid EdDSA+ML-DSA, verified server-side against the real gem." %>

<section class="space-y-8">
  <header class="space-y-4">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight">Post-quantum JWT for Ruby</h1>
    <p class="text-xl text-slate-700">
      jwt-pq signs and verifies JSON Web Tokens with ML-DSA (FIPS 204), the
      post-quantum digital signature standardized by NIST in 2024. An optional
      hybrid mode layers classical EdDSA on top so a break in either algorithm
      alone does not break the token.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Why now</h2>
    <p>
      A sufficiently large quantum computer breaks every elliptic-curve and
      RSA signature on the wire today. Nobody knows when that machine arrives,
      but tokens signed this year may still be in audit logs, archived S3
      buckets, and signed bundles a decade from now. Migrating signature
      algorithms is a multi-year operation — library support, key rotation,
      verifier rollout, revocation. The time to start is before you have to.
    </p>
    <p>
      NIST finalized ML-DSA in FIPS 204 in August 2024. The COSE working group
      has an active draft mapping ML-DSA into the JOSE/COSE ecosystem
      (<code>draft-ietf-cose-dilithium</code>). jwt-pq tracks that draft: the
      <code>alg</code> values, the <code>AKP</code> key type, the JWK shape.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">30-second example</h2>
    <pre class="bg-slate-50 p-4 rounded text-sm overflow-auto"><code class="language-ruby">require "jwt/pq"

key    = JWT::PQ::Key.generate(:ml_dsa_65)
token  = JWT.encode({ sub: "u-1" }, key, "ML-DSA-65")

decoded, header = JWT.decode(token, key, true, algorithms: ["ML-DSA-65"])
header["alg"]   # =&gt; "ML-DSA-65"
decoded["sub"]  # =&gt; "u-1"</code></pre>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      Keys export to JWK (<code>kty: "AKP"</code>) and PEM (SPKI / PKCS#8).
      A matching hybrid API (<code>JWT::PQ::HybridKey</code>, alg
      <code>EdDSA+ML-DSA-65</code>) concatenates an Ed25519 signature with the
      ML-DSA one for defense in depth.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Where next</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><%= link_to "Quick start", quickstart_path, class: "underline" %> — install and sign in five minutes.</li>
      <li><%= link_to "Algorithms", algorithms_path, class: "underline" %> — ML-DSA-44 / 65 / 87: which to pick.</li>
      <li><%= link_to "Hybrid", hybrid_path, class: "underline" %> — when EdDSA+ML-DSA beats ML-DSA alone.</li>
      <li><%= link_to "Security", security_path, class: "underline" %> — what the gem guarantees and what it does not.</li>
      <li><%= link_to "Debugger", debugger_path, class: "underline" %> — paste a token, verify against the live gem.</li>
      <li><code>/.well-known/jwks.json</code> — long-lived demo JWKS for integration testing.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</section>
